@alexfauquette  @Tenison @tvrashid @guyonroche
Any luck on this issue ? While importing an excel file using **exceljs .xlsx in ReactJs + Typescript** I receive a similar error 

```
import { Workbook } from 'exceljs';
import { Importer } from 'xlsx-import/lib/Importer';
import Dropzone, { FileWithPath, useDropzone } from "react-dropzone";

async function handleFileUpload() {
    return Promise.resolve(fetch('invoice.xlsx').then((r) => r.blob()));
}

    const onDrop = useCallback(async(acceptedFiles: File[]) => {
      setFiles(acceptedFiles);
      const reader = new FileReader();
      const invoiceFile = await handleFileUpload()
      reader.readAsArrayBuffer(invoiceFile);
      reader.addEventListener('loadend', async e => {
            if (reader.result instanceof ArrayBuffer) {
                        const wb =  new Workbook();
                        await wb.xlsx.load(reader.result);
                        const importer = new Importer(wb);
                        setInvoice(onImportInvoice(importer));
            }
    })


```

I am getting this Error on the line [const wb =  new Workbook();] 

```
index.tsx:86 Uncaught (in promise) TypeError: exceljs__WEBPACK_IMPORTED_MODULE_1__.Workbook is not a constructor
    at FileReader.<anonymous> (index.tsx:86:1)
```

I used excelJS. In my use case, I clone a file template.xlsx and inserted some data. I then saved it to another file at the end. Hope this helps.

```js
const runMainTemplate = () => {
    const workbook = new ExcelJS.Workbook();
    //file name to clone
    let filename = 'template.xlsx';

    workbook.xlsx.readFile(filename)
    .then(function() {
        //Accessing Sheet to clone
        let sheetA = workbook.getWorksheet("Sheet1");
        let sheetB = workbook.getWorksheet("Sheet2");
        

        insertMonthlyDataIntoTemplate(sheetA);
        //Creating new sheet
        // let row = sheetB.getRow(5);
        // row.getCell(1).value = 5; // A5's value set to 5
        // row.commit();

        return workbook.xlsx.writeFile("finalsavepoint.xlsx");
    }); 
} 

const insertMonthlyDataIntoTemplate = (worksheet) => {
    worksheet.getCell('P7').value = todaysDate();
    worksheet.getCell('Q4').value = "PERCENTAGE  SERVICE AVAILABILITY FOR THE MONTH: " + metaDataHolder.monthlyPercentage + "%";
    worksheet.getCell('I4').value = "TRANSMISSION STATION: " + metaDataHolder.station;

}
```

In my case, I had importation issues because I wanted to use ES6 imports instead of CommonJS. I managed to solve it with the following import statement.
``` javascript
import exceljs from 'exceljs';
const { Workbook } = exceljs;
const workbook = new Workbook();

```
**Remember that if you want to use ES6, you need to change the "type" to "module" in the package.json.**

> In my case, I had importation issues because I wanted to use ES6 imports instead of CommonJS. I managed to solve it with the following import statement.
> 
> ```js
> import exceljs from 'exceljs';
> const { Workbook } = exceljs;
> const workbook = new Workbook();
> ```
> 
> **Remember that if you want to use ES6, you need to change the "type" to "module" in the package.json.**

Thank you. This worked for me in my ESM set up.
